==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|accompaignier||to associate with}}, from ''[[compaign]]'', {{term|compain||companion}}. See [[company]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈkʌm.pə.ni/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accompany.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|accompan|i|ed}}

# {{intransitive|obsolete}} {{rfdate|really quote Bacon}} To associate in a company; to keep company. — [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]]
#* {{rfdate}} ''Men say that they will drive away one another, … and not '''accompany''' together.'' — Holland
# {{intransitive|obsolete}} {{rfdate|really quote Milton}} To [[cohabit]] (with). — [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]
# {{intransitive|music}} To perform an accompanying part or parts in a [[composition]].
# {{transitive}} To go with or attend as a companion or associate; to keep company with; to go along with.
#* ''He '''accompanied''' his speech with a bow.''
#* {{rfdate}} ''The Persian dames, … / In sumptuous cars, '''accompanied''' his march.'' — [[w:Richard Glover (poet)|Glover]]
#* {{rfdate}} ''They are never alone that are '''accompanied''' with noble thoughts.'' — [[w:Sir P. Sidney|Sir P. Sidney]]
#* {{rfdate}} ''He was '''accompanied''' by two carts filled with wounded rebels.'' — [[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]]
# {{transitive|obsolete}} {{rfdate|really quote Herbert}} To cohabit with — [[w:Sir_Thomas_Herbert,_1st_Baronet|Sir T. Herbert]]
# {{transitive|music}} To perform an accompanying part next to another instrument.
#* ''The strings were '''accompanied''' by two woodwinds.''
{{rfex|the obsolete cases}}

=====Synonyms=====
* {{italbrac|go with}} [[attend]], [[escort]], go with
:* We '''accompany''' those with whom we go as companions. The word imports an ''equality'' of station.
:* We '''attend''' those whom we wait upon or follow. The word conveys an idea of ''subordination''.
:* We '''escort''' those whom we attend with a view to ''guard and protect''.
:*: A gentleman '''accompanies''' a friend to some public place; he '''attends''' or '''escorts''' a lady.

